[8] Australia (Rockingham)
Date: Mon 21 Oct 2019
Source: Western Suburbs Weekly [abridged, edited]
https://www.communitynews.com.au/western-suburbs-weekly/news/department-of-health-acts-on-measles-spike


The Department of Health has urged people at risk to take up their offer of free measles vaccination following the "highly unusual" cluster of cases confirmed over the past 2 months.

There have been 26 confirmed cases of measles associated with the cluster from the Rockingham area, prompting health authorities to renew their plea for vaccination checks, specifically targeting Western Australians between 20 and 53 years old.

"That is in recognition of the fact that people of that age group may not have gotten 2 doses of measles vaccine when they were children because vaccination schedules were different back in those days," she said. "They are people who are definitely at risk now, and so we urge them to get vaccinated as soon as possible and check their immunisation status."

Communicable disease control director Donna Mak said the last time WA [Western Australia] had a cluster this big was nearly 10 years ago.

"It's been a long, long time, and thank goodness for that, because we wouldn't want this to be happening on a daily basis," she said. "We have had 53 cases this year [2019] to date in WA. This is highly unusual; usually we would see a handful of cases every year."

A former measles patient from Busselton spent 5 nights in the ICU in Bunbury for measles, which was believed to be from his trip to Singapore in early July [2019].

"I had flu-like symptoms. I had no idea," he said. "I didn't really think Singapore would be a hotbed of measles, to be perfectly honest. It took a couple of days to determine these were measles."

[The former patient] said he was in the negative pressure room, in complete isolation with no air escaping, for 5 nights and took about 3 weeks to fully recover.

[Byline: Nadia Budihardjo]

