[10] New Zealand
Date: Mon 21 Oct 2019
Source: News Hub [abridged, edited]
https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/politics/2019/10/tax-cuts-would-threaten-fight-against-measles-associate-health-minister-julie-anne-genter.html


Associate health minister Julie Anne Genter says if National goes into the next election promising tax cuts, it'll be at the expense of the fight against measles.

More than 1800 people have been infected with the highly virulent disease in the present outbreak, about 1500 of them in Auckland alone. Measles has the ability to weaken the body's immunity to other diseases and can even be fatal.

Appearing on The AM Show on Monday [21 Oct 2019] morning, Genter defended the government's efforts to control the virus' spread.

"If you look at the 1st 10 months of this year [2019], already we've administered over 300 000 vaccines. We've got another 107 500 being distributed around the country right now and another 155 000 coming in the next few months."

Shortages have remained, however, which Genter blamed on an "unprecedented number of people looking to get vaccinated" in a 2-week stretch in September [2019].

Measles cases have been rising worldwide over the past few years. In the 1st 3 months of 2019, there were 4 times as many cases than in the 1st 3 months of 2018.

Asked if the initial response here in New Zealand was too slow, Genter blamed a lack of funds initially available.

Ministry of Health data shows only 88% of present-day children are fully immunised, and some Generation X/older Millennials might not be immune at all due to historical gaps in coverage.

Genter said there are presently enough vaccines to ensure everyone under 15 is able to get immunised. A catch-up campaign for young adults is planned for "early next year [2020]."

According to the World Health Organization, New Zealand has been technically measles-free since 2017. That means there are no homegrown outbreaks, and any outbreaks caused by someone bringing the virus into the country is eliminated within 12 months.

New Zealand has until March next year [2020] to end the present outbreak to retain that status, vaccinologist Helen Petousis-Harris told RNZ in August [2019].

National has not said whether it would cut taxes if elected in 2020, but it's likely. The party's promised tax cuts at the 2017 election didn't come to pass because it lost.

[Byline: Dan Satherley]

