[18] Pennsylvania
Date: Thu 24 Oct 2019
https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/23/health/measles-quarantine-pennsylvania-woman/


A Pennsylvania woman has been ordered quarantined after she was potentially exposed to measles, the 1st time the city ordered a quarantine in decades, according to a city spokesman.

T.B. visited Lehigh Valley Health Network on 12 Oct [2019] during a time when people there may have been exposed to measles, according to a court petition. When she was notified of her possible exposure, she was informed that a vaccine could provide immunity but did not show up to get the vaccine and did not prove immunity to the Allentown Health Bureau, the petition says.

The petition says T.B. indicated she would not comply with the quarantine. In response, the Health Bureau went to court, and on Monday [21 Oct 2019], Judge Edward Reibman ordered her to stay in her home until 3 Nov [2019], or until the Health Bureau decides that she is noncommunicable.

T.B. is one of 5 people in the city to be directed to stay under quarantine due to measles concerns, Mike Moore, a spokesman for the city, said in a statement. Moore said that none of the 5 are currently displaying symptoms of measles. During her quarantine, the Allentown Health Bureau is responsible for providing T.B. food and other necessities, the order states.

Allentown Health Bureau director Vicky Kistler said it is the 1st time such a court order was issued in about 2 decades, according to Moore's statement.

The Pennsylvania Department of Health said in a statement that confirmed measles cases are up in 2019. It said there have been 16 confirmed cases this year [2019], while there were only 2 last year [2018].

[Byline: Josh Girsky and Amanda Sealy]

